---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';


const path = '/compare/postscript-vs-activecampaign';
const title = 'Postscript vs ActiveCampaign for Shopify: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Postscript vs ActiveCampaign for Shopify — SMS-native DTC tooling vs automation-heavy CRM email, stack splits, and when each channel owner wins.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Postscript or ActiveCampaign better for Shopify SMS?',
    answer: 'Postscript is SMS-native with Shopify cart triggers, keyword opt-in, two-way conversations, and TCPA guardrails. ActiveCampaign offers SMS as an add-on to its automation and CRM platform — workable for moderate volume tied to complex email automations. Choose Postscript when SMS is a primary DTC channel. Choose ActiveCampaign SMS only when text volume is low and automation logic must live in the same tool as email CRM.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can ActiveCampaign replace Postscript?',
    answer: 'Not for SMS-heavy Shopify DTC. ActiveCampaign SMS lacks Postscript depth on compliance dashboards, conversational reply routing, and Shopify drop-campaign patterns. ActiveCampaign replaces Postscript when your business is automation-first — courses, B2B wholesale, membership — with SMS as a thin layer on top of CRM pipelines, not flash-sale infrastructure.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I use ActiveCampaign for email and Postscript for SMS?',
    answer: 'Common for merchants who chose ActiveCampaign before SMS mattered — complex automations, deal stages, and lead scoring stay in ActiveCampaign; Postscript owns promotional and recovery text. Sync suppressions and purchase events bidirectionally. The failure mode is duplicate cart touches because ActiveCampaign automation and Postscript flows trigger on different timers without coordination.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Postscript vs ActiveCampaign pricing compare?',
    answer: 'Postscript: plan plus per-message usage scaled to promotional volume. ActiveCampaign: contact-tier pricing plus SMS credits on higher plans — CRM features inflate base cost before sending a single text. Compare total stack cost: ActiveCampaign at 20k contacts plus Postscript SMS often exceeds Klaviyo for equivalent ecommerce retention unless CRM automation is genuinely load-bearing.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of ActiveCampaign or Postscript?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy targets ecommerce email lifecycle with pay-per-email economics — not CRM deal pipelines. Replace ActiveCampaign email with Sequenzy if CRM complexity is overkill for DTC; keep ActiveCampaign if B2B wholesale and sales automation are core. Pair Sequenzy or ActiveCampaign email with Postscript for SMS — neither replaces Postscript for text depth.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles Shopify ecommerce triggers better?',
    answer: 'Postscript is built around Shopify cart, checkout, and order events for SMS. ActiveCampaign Shopify integration supports ecommerce automations but shines on tag-based CRM logic, form submissions, and multi-step nurture — better for hybrid B2B/DTC than pure flash-sale DTC. Supplement wholesale plus DTC shops often live in ActiveCampaign; mobile-first fashion lives in Postscript.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better automation depth?',
    answer: 'ActiveCampaign wins email and CRM automation — conditional branches, lead scoring, deal stages, site tracking. Postscript automation is SMS-scoped — cart, keyword, broadcast, conversational. If your retention strategy requires CRM sophistication, ActiveCampaign remains email brain; Postscript does not replace that regardless of SMS performance.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'SMS tests: keyword opt-in, cart abandonment with reply, flash broadcast with quiet hours — Postscript should win. CRM tests: lead tagging from wholesale inquiry form, multi-branch nurture based on product interest, deal stage SMS nudge — ActiveCampaign should win if those workflows exist. If you only run DTC ecommerce without CRM, question why ActiveCampaign SMS is in the conversation at all.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Postscript vs ActiveCampaign</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Postscript vs ActiveCampaign for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          ActiveCampaign sells automation and CRM depth; Postscript sells Shopify SMS infrastructure. We evaluated both through a hybrid artisan coffee brand running wholesale CRM in ActiveCampaign and DTC drop texts on Postscript, an outdoor gear educator using ActiveCampaign SMS for workshop reminders with no Postscript need, and a vinyl record shop that migrated off ActiveCampaign entirely once SMS revenue exposed the wrong tool for each channel.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Shopify SMS', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'Drop campaigns, cart recovery, and TCPA tooling for DTC.' },
            { label: 'CRM automation', tool: 'ActiveCampaign', reason: 'Deal stages, lead scoring, and complex email branches.' },
            { label: 'Two-way text', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'Conversational recovery for product questions on mobile.' },
            { label: 'Hybrid B2B + DTC', tool: 'ActiveCampaign', reason: 'Wholesale pipelines alongside consumer email automations.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Ecommerce email lifecycle if CRM complexity is overkill for DTC.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Postscript</th><th>ActiveCampaign</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>SMS-native Shopify DTC</td><td>CRM-heavy email automation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Usage-based plans</td><td>From ~$29/mo; SMS on higher tiers</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Plan + per-message</td><td>Contacts + SMS credits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Email depth</td><td>Not included</td><td>Core — automation and CRM</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS depth</td><td>Best-in-class for Shopify</td><td>Add-on for automation triggers</td></tr>
            <tr><td>CRM / deals</td><td>Not applicable</td><td>Core strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify DTC drops</td><td>Primary design center</td><td>Secondary to automation logic</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical role</td><td>SMS channel owner</td><td>Email CRM brain + optional SMS</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Postscript and ActiveCampaign sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Postscript is optimized when SMS is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline. ActiveCampaign is optimized when wholesale pipelines and site tracking share one automation brain. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>Mechanical Keyboard Vendor ($58k/mo) — halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed</h2>
        <p>
          The mechanical keyboard vendor does 940 orders/mo at roughly $58k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows six-week group-buy cycles on $180–$420 kits, which means email must handle GB close suppression and switch-type education across five PDPs before GB close deadlines — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; ActiveCampaign contributes CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. ActiveCampaign remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Consideration length changed channel choice. Keyboard shoppers compared switches for ten days before carting; email education outperformed early discount codes. The platform that surfaced browse depth without manual list exports saved roughly six hours a week during GB season. For mechanical keyboard vendor specifically, halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise GB close deadlines becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Essen release week: board game store retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The board game store does 1,050 orders/mo at roughly $67k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles, which means email must handle pre-order state machines and fulfillment pivots after allocation closes before Essen release week — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; ActiveCampaign contributes CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, ActiveCampaign reduced preview-time surprises because CRM pipelines. Postscript remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For board game store specifically, pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Essen release week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Specialty Tea Merchant: 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality</h2>
        <p>
          The specialty tea merchant does 720 orders/mo at roughly $44k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality, which means email must handle subscription skip handling and gift-buyer exclusions in December before Q4 gift-box peak — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; ActiveCampaign contributes CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. ActiveCampaign remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          High-AOV safety content beats coupons. Climbing shoppers wanted retirement timelines and certification context; a 10% off rope email on day two would have trained worst practices. Education-first sequencing recovered more margin than blanket promos. For specialty tea merchant specifically, split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Q4 gift-box peak becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How artisan coffee roaster emails through holiday blend drop</h2>
        <p>
          The artisan coffee roaster does 860 orders/mo at roughly $52k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows roast-date replenishment and wholesale sample follow-ups, which means email must handle bean reorder at day thirty with subscription pause confirmations before holiday blend drop — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; ActiveCampaign contributes CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, ActiveCampaign reduced preview-time surprises because CRM pipelines. Postscript remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For artisan coffee roaster specifically, suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday blend drop becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Climbing Gear Store ($89k/mo) — branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages</h2>
        <p>
          The climbing gear store does 1,100 orders/mo at roughly $89k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows seven-to-fourteen day harness research cycles, which means email must handle certification education before percentage-off nudges on ropes before spring rack refresh — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; ActiveCampaign contributes CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, ActiveCampaign reduced preview-time surprises because CRM pipelines. Postscript remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For climbing gear store specifically, branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise spring rack refresh becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Memorial Day camping spike: camping equipment merchant retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The camping equipment merchant does 1,350 orders/mo at roughly $78k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows tent-capacity quizzes and family car-camping segments, which means email must handle trip-season browse recovery on mobile PDPs before cart before Memorial Day camping spike — not after support tickets spike. Postscript contributes Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails; ActiveCampaign contributes CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Postscript reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails. ActiveCampaign remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Waitlist psychology is not welcome psychology. Pottery class leads needed studio policies and kiln safety; glaze-kit promos on day one felt like bait-and-switch. Branching welcome by signup source prevented the mismatch. For camping equipment merchant specifically, route quiz outcomes into different welcome branches before tent promos. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day camping spike becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>ActiveCampaign workflow reality: strengths, friction, and billing</h2>
        <p>
          Postscript shines when SMS is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline. Its friction shows when email newsletters and lifecycle are the main stack. ActiveCampaign shines when wholesale pipelines and site tracking share one automation brain. Its friction shows when pure DTC Shopify retention is the only job. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Postscript (message volume and plans) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. ActiveCampaign (contacts plus feature tier) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Postscript and ActiveCampaign both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like ActiveCampaign punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Postscript, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Postscript if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Sms is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline</li>
          <li>You will use Shopify-native SMS with compliance guardrails weekly</li>
          <li>Message volume and plans fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Postscript without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Postscript for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose ActiveCampaign if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Wholesale pipelines and site tracking share one automation brain</li>
          <li>You will use CRM pipelines, lead scoring, and automation logic weekly</li>
          <li>Contacts plus feature tier fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain ActiveCampaign without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies ActiveCampaign migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Postscript is the better Shopify email tool when SMS is a primary revenue channel with compliance discipline. ActiveCampaign is the better Shopify email tool when wholesale pipelines and site tracking share one automation brain. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/drip-vs-activecampaign">Drip vs ActiveCampaign</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/activecampaign-vs-klaviyo">ActiveCampaign vs Klaviyo</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/postscript-vs-mailchimp">Postscript vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/supplements">Email tools for supplement stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Postscript vs ActiveCampaign FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
